This means that if your operation is long running (or blocks for some reason), you will need to perform the operation on separate thread, but, you should also never update the the UI from outside the context of the Event Dispatching Thread. Adding abstraction adds some overhead, so if you are avoiding typing something out only 2 or 3 times, it's not such a good deal.  But if you are doing `is_empty` checks all over the place, it is a huge win to simplify all your checks AND keep them consistent at the same time.

Your explanation of why `"foo" -?` doesn't work is incorrect. The actual reason is that PowerShell doesn't interpret strings as commands unless you use the call operator (`&`). Bare strings are automatically echoed to the success output stream. If you put something beginning with a hyphen after a string that gets interpreted as an operator (but an operator `-?` doesn't exist). `& "foo" -?` would work if `foo` were a valid command. Compare for instance the output of `"Copy-Item" -?` and `& "Copy-Item" -?`.

No. If you intend to develop for the web, you should familiarize yourself with the HTTP protocol. Data is either passed in the URL as a query string or in the request body. While the spec doesn't specifically prohibit GET requests from having a request body, there's no client I know of that natively supports that. In other words, for GET, all you've got is the query string. If you do a POST, you can send the data as part of the request body, so it's at least not visible in the address bar, but there's no true way to hide the data. Anyone can inspect the request body if they want.

There is nothing wrong with retrieving a `TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE` as a `Instant`. I'm having a hard time understanding what you're asking. When the `Serialize()` method returns, it's done. It's serialized your object. Even if that method returned a byte count, you wouldn't be able to prepend the serialized object's data with the byte count unless you serialize to a local buffer first instead of writing directly to the `NetworkStream`. You said "Waiting for children is not needed", which is accurate, but the criterion is actually stronger than that.  It is crucial, in general, that the code does not wait for the children as you may very well get blockages because one process generates more data than can fit in the pipe buffer (which was historically 5 KiB; POSIX only requires 4 KiB; but many modern O/S use 64 KiB).  Also, because the parent hasn't closed file descriptors when waiting, the processes can be deadlocked if the parent waits.
